,Not Recommended,425720,28962879,Posted: 2 January,all,Empress Dowager,fun for 5 min
76561197968761535,Not Recommended,425720,23837770,"Posted: 26 June, 2016",all,AnD4D,"I originally bought this game back in April, before I got my Vive. I refunded it after minutes of playing it. The Vive wasn't designed to spend so long staring at the ground. On top of that, graphics were flickering, and at one point, the world started twisting and swaying, forcing me to pull the headset off, and gave me a headache for 2 hours.In the Summer sale, I thought I'd try it again. After all, months later, the game may have improved.Well... no. Not really. The graphical glitches are still there, with textures visible loading in, but that's not the problem.The game, for me at least, is too faulty by design. For example, after teleporting to the ball, rather than repositioning the player in a logical position, the game simply does so based on a fixed geographical angle. By this I mean if you're facing North when you hit the ball, and the direction between the resulting shot lines the ball and the hole in a south direction... when you teleport, you'll remain facing North, rather than the game predicting where you should be standing. This means that you then have to walk around the room in a tiny circle, making sure that you, physically, are now facing the correct direction.This results in the Vive, with its tethered cables, constantly twisting up. On top of this, the number of times I accidentally touched the ball with my bat while I'm turning around, and adding to my 'score'. This could easily be prevented by having the player pull the trigger or push the touch pad to retract the club, or even require it to be held when taking a shot. Of course, this wouldn't really be an issue if they just fixed the orientation.With this in mind, swapping the headset during a multiplayer game, each turn, doubled, tripled or even quadrupled the tangling issue. After our 2 minute game, my wife and I had to spend a few minutes unravelling the headset.The fixes for these 2 issues are easy and should be obvious. A path finding system would enable the game to predict where the player would want to stand, and effectively rotate the level for them, rather than them needing to rotate so much.Order of play should be based on last on, first on. This means to say whomever has the headset on at the end of the hole gets to play the first hole on the next game. This reduces (potentially halves) the number of times the headset needs to be taken off. At the moment, the game lets whomever is winning stay on. This means that a close game makes it hard to predict who is next to play.I'll not risk my headset cabled getting damaged simply because the developers can't figure out such simple solutions.At one point, we started the game, and immediately accidently touched the ball. Even though it hadn't even left the wooden start space, it counted that as a hit. We then quit the game, and tried to start again. From here, we couldnt figure out how the change the player names. As we'd done it once before, the game didn't ask us a second time. Very frustrating. I'd like to be able to choose who goes first.Another bug bear is that the menu itself is a golf game. ""Want to play? Knock the ball into this gate!"" Why slow down a menu? Just allow us to point and select. I don't want to play a game so that I can play the game!Finally, the hit detection is odd. At one point, I swang the club quite fast, and it went through the ball. It moved less than an inch, but still classed it as a stroke. Add that to the fact that there didn't appear to be any music playing, and the game was more hassle than fun."
